Hong Kong officials said Tuesday an additional 75 people were hit by severe acute respiratory syndrome, or SARS, including 52 from the Amoy Gardens complex. It was not immediately clear how many of the new cases had come from Block E, which was sealed off Monday with barricades and police tape. Residents were told they would have to stay inside for 10 days, with regular medical checkups and three free meals a day provided. But officials soon began floating the idea of making quarantine centers in the holiday camps and they took that step Tuesday night. ^ MORE &lt; 